  <title>The Basel Problem: A Fourier Series Proof</title>
  <dc:creator>John P. Lake</dc:creator>
  <link>https://johnplake.github.io/blog/posts/basel-problem/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<section id="the-basel-problem" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-basel-problem">The Basel Problem</h2>
<p>One of the most elegant results in analysis is the evaluation of the infinite series:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%5E2%7D%7B6%7D"></p>
<p>This problem stumped mathematicians for decades until Euler solved it in 1734. While Euler‚Äôs original proof was ingenious but not entirely rigorous, the Fourier series approach provides a clean, modern proof.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-setup" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-setup">The Setup</h2>
<p>Consider the function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x)%20=%20x"> on the interval <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5B-%5Cpi,%20%5Cpi%5D">, extended periodically. The Fourier series for this function is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x)%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20b_n%20%5Csin(nx)"></p>
<p>where the coefficients are given by:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?b_n%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cint_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20x%20%5Csin(nx)%20%5C,%20dx"></p>
</section>
<section id="computing-the-coefficients" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="computing-the-coefficients">Computing the Coefficients</h2>
<p>Let‚Äôs evaluate this integral using integration by parts:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0Ab_n%20&amp;=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cint_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20x%20%5Csin(nx)%20%5C,%20dx%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cleft%5B%20-%5Cfrac%7Bx%20%5Ccos(nx)%7D%7Bn%7D%20%5Cbigg%7C_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20+%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn%7D%20%5Cint_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Ccos(nx)%20%5C,%20dx%20%5Cright%5D%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cleft%5B%20-%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%20%5Ccos(n%5Cpi)%7D%7Bn%7D%20+%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Csin(nx)%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D%20%5Cbigg%7C_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cright%5D%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></p>
<p>Since <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ccos(n%5Cpi)%20=%20(-1)%5En"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csin(n%5Cpi)%20=%200">, we get:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?b_n%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Ccdot%20%5Cfrac%7B-%5Cpi(-1)%5En%7D%7Bn%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B-2(-1)%5En%7D%7Bn%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2(-1)%5E%7Bn+1%7D%7D%7Bn%7D"></p>
<p>So our Fourier series is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B2(-1)%5E%7Bn+1%7D%7D%7Bn%7D%20%5Csin(nx),%20%5Cquad%20x%20%5Cin%20(-%5Cpi,%20%5Cpi)"></p>
</section>
<section id="parsevals-identity" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="parsevals-identity">Parseval‚Äôs Identity</h2>
<p>Here‚Äôs where the magic happens. Parseval‚Äôs identity tells us that for a function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f"> with Fourier series:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cint_%7B-%5Cpi%7D%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%7Cf(x)%7C%5E2%20%5C,%20dx%20=%20%5Cfrac%7Ba_0%5E2%7D%7B2%7D%20+%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20(a_n%5E2%20+%20b_n%5E2)"></p>
<p>For our function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x)%20=%20x">, we have only sine terms, so <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a_n%20=%200"> for all <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">. Thus:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cint_%7B-%5Cpi%7D%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20x%5E2%20%5C,%20dx%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20b_n%5E2"></p>
</section>
<section id="the-calculation" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-calculation">The Calculation</h2>
<p>The left side is straightforward:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Cint_%7B-%5Cpi%7D%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20x%5E2%20%5C,%20dx%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Ccdot%20%5Cfrac%7B2x%5E3%7D%7B3%7D%20%5Cbigg%7C_0%5E%7B%5Cpi%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%20%5Ccdot%20%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%5E3%7D%7B3%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%5E2%7D%7B3%7D"></p>
<p>The right side gives us:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20b_n%5E2%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cleft(%5Cfrac%7B2(-1)%5E%7Bn+1%7D%7D%7Bn%7D%5Cright)%5E2%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B4%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D%20=%204%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D"></p>
</section>
<section id="the-final-step" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-final-step">The Final Step</h2>
<p>Equating both sides:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%5E2%7D%7B3%7D%20=%204%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D"></p>
<p>Therefore:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn%5E2%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%5E2%7D%7B12%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%5E2%7D%7B6%7D"></p>
<p>And we‚Äôre done! The Basel problem falls elegantly from the machinery of Fourier analysis. üêü</p>
</section>
<section id="why-this-matters" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-this-matters">Why This Matters</h2>
<p>This proof showcases the power of Fourier series not just for solving differential equations or signal processing, but for evaluating seemingly unrelated infinite series. The connection between the geometry of periodic functions and number-theoretic sums remains one of the most beautiful bridges in mathematics.</p>


</section>

 ]]></description>
